> And in fact we can even use kernel threads most of the time.<p>Well, not if you need tens-of-thousands of them or more.<p>> However, there is one thread you don&#x27;t want to block: the UI thread.<p>No problem. You simply multiplex fibers onto the UI thread, where they can block all they want. Here&#x27;s an example in Quasar (Java):<p><pre><code>    FiberScheduler uiScheduler = new FiberExecutorScheduler(&quot;UI-scheduler&quot;, 
       task -> EventQueue.invokeLater(task)); // schedule on the UI thread

    new Fiber(uiScheduler, () -> {
            for (i = 0;; i++) {
                assert EventQueue.isDispatchThread(); // I&#x27;m on the UI thread!
                uiLabel.setText(&quot;num: &quot; + i); // I can update the ui
                Fiber.sleep(1000); // ... yet I can block all I want
            }
        }).start();</code></pre>

Can you explain how tuples are significantly different from multiple returns in real programs?  You can do<p><pre><code>    func foo() (string, int, bool) {
        return &quot;one&quot;, 2, true
    }

    func bar(s string, i int, b bool) {}

    bar(foo())</code></pre>
